(Advanced) Quest 11: Capstone Project - NFT Marketplace Frontend
Introduction
In Quest 8 we created and deployed our ERC721 smart contract to the Avalanche Fuji Testnet. In Quest 10, we created the Auction and Auction Manager smart contracts and deployed it to the Testnet as well. This quest, we will combine everything together by building a frontend that interacts with all three smart contracts in an NFT auctioning marketplace.
If you haven’t completed the aforementioned quests, please do so before proceeding with this quest.

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Use advanced functions of the ethers.js library
  • Build a frontend that connects to deployed smart contracts on a Testnet
  • Build an NFT auctioning marketplace
Deliverable
This quest has one deliverable.
  1. A screenshot of three tabs of SnowTrace block explorers. Follow instructions in Step 15 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Setting Up Second Account
We’ll start off by setting up a second Core account as there are two roles that we’ll need to simulate two roles for our web application - the NFT owner and a bidder. This is because NFT owners cannot place bids for their own NFTs, as is defined in our code in Quest 10.
To add a second account to your Core wallet, you will first need to open up the Core extension. Then, press on the dropdown arrow besides your account name at the top of the wallet. Press on + Create Account and give this account the name of Bidder.



So now that you have created your second account, you will need to know how to switch accounts. On the pop up, you can click on your desired account by clicking on it and that will switch your currently activated Core account to that account. The currently selected account will be highlighted. For example, in the image above, the account that is currently selected is Bidder.

For now, switch back to your first account since we’ll need to play the role of the NFT owner first.
Step 2: Requirements
You’ll need to have Git installed on your machine to clone the project repository. You can check if git is installed by using the following command. This command would return you the git version if git has been installed. If you don’t have git installed, you can refer to the following guides for how to install git to your machine:
  • Windows guide
  • Mac guide

git --version

Lastly, you’ll need a code/text editor of your choice. You are free to use any code editor of your choice, but our recommendation is Visual Studio Code.
Step 3: Project Setup
Alright, you know the drill by now, we’ll start by cloning the project files for this quest.
git clone -b avax-quest-11 https://github.com/stackup-dev/advancing-into-avalanche.git

Then, change the directory of your terminal to enter the project repository. We can do so with the command below.

cd advancing-into-avalanche

Once we are in the base directory of the project, we will once again need to install the libraries using the following command. 

npm install

Once the libraries are installed, we will need to start the React server. We can do so using the command below.

npm run start

Now that we have our server running, we can now proceed to create the contract objects that will interact with our smart contracts.
Step 4: Recap of Smart Contracts
To recap, there are three smart contracts we’ll be interacting with - the NFT, auction and the auction manager smart contracts.  
In Quest 8, we learnt that the NFT smart contract contains functions such as minting, transferring of NFT, getting various token information etc. In this quest, we will mainly be calling the functions pertaining to getting token information and transferring of NFTs. In other words, we won’t be using the mint function of the smart contract since we already minted our NFTs in Quest 9.

In Quest 10, we learnt that the auction smart contract allows us to get information about the auction, place a bid, withdraw funds or the token and cancel the auction. In this quest, we will be using all of these functions. 

Also in Quest 10, we learnt that the auction manager smart contract manages all the auction smart contracts. It is able to create auctions, get a list of auctions and their information. Similarly, we’ll be utilizing all of these functions in this quest.
Step 5: Connecting to Deployed Smart Contracts
Now that our memory is refreshed, let’s go ahead to create the contract objects that we’ll use to interact with our deployed smart contracts. Similar to Quest 9, most of the code behind the NFT marketplace will be found in src/App.js as this is the main body of our React web application.
Open up the App.js file in your code editor. The first thing that we need to configure is the NFT and the auction manager smart contract addresses. You can obtain the NFT address from Quest 8 where we uploaded the ERC721 token smart contract. The auction manager smart contract address can be obtained from Quest 10. Since we searched for both of these contracts on SnowTrace at the end of their respective quests, you should be able to find the SnowTrace pages from your browser history and thus get the deployed contract addresses.

To recap, we need the smart contract addresses so that the contract object is able to point to the correct deployed smart contract on the blockchain. Once you have both addresses, replace the values in lines 6 and 7 respectively.

As we have learned in Quest 9, to initialize a contract object, you will need the following three pieces of information - contract address, contract ABI and the wallet signer object. 

To initialize the two contract objects, you will need to add the following lines of code to line 30. This is similar to what we have done before in Quest 9 so you should be familiar with how this works.

this._auctionManager = new ethers.Contract(     AUCTIONMANAGER_ADDRESS,     AuctionManagerArtifact.abi,     this.signer    ); this._nft = new ethers.Contract(     NFT_ADDRESS,     NFTArtifact.abi,     this.signer    );

However, to initialize the auction smart contract object, you will need to add the following lines of code below inside the setActiveAution() function instead (around line 68). We do this because there is no fixed address for the auction contract object, i.e. the address changes for every auction. Therefore, we need the auction smart contract address to be dynamic and not fixed so that we can change it to the auction smart contract that we are dealing with.

_this._auction = new ethers.Contract(    auction.auctionAddress,    AuctionArtifact.abi,    _this.signer  );

Now that we have initialized our contract objects, we will look at how we can get NFTs that are owned by the wallet address.
Step 6: Getting the NFTs
In Quest 9, we minted some NFTs using our memory game. Now, we will be retrieving a list of the IDs of the NFTs that we have minted. We do this because it’ll be useful for the owner to be able to see what NFTs can be put up for auction on the marketplace.
const walletAddress = await this.signer.getAddress();  let tokenOwner = null;  let counter = 0;  const NFTIds = [];  do {   try {    tokenOwner = await this._nft.ownerOf(counter);    if (tokenOwner === walletAddress) {     NFTIds.push(counter);    }    counter++;   } catch (error) {    tokenOwner = null;  }    } while (tokenOwner != null);  this.setState({ myItems: NFTIds });

Above is the code for getting the NFTs, you’ll need to paste it into the getItems() function (around line 49).

Since token IDs are assigned on an incremental basis starting from 0, the code works by querying the owner of the tokens starting from token ID 0 and if the owner address matches the wallet address, it adds that to an array. This continues until there is an error which means that the current token ID is not assigned to any address and that will stop the loop. 

In Quest 10, we learnt that the function ownerOf() returns the address of the NFT owner of the ID that we provide. We use this function to get the NFT owners’ address to see if it matches the user’s wallet address.  

After saving your script, you’ll notice that on your webpage, a list of your token IDs is now displayed (view ‘Expected output’ for a reference). You should have at least until id: 3. If you played the card matching game multiple times, you will have more up to more ids. If you don’t see anything, make sure that you’re using the Core account containing the NFTs.

So now that we have gone through how to fetch the list of NFT IDs for a specific address, in the next step we will go through how we can create an auction!

Step 7: Creating an Auction
For this step, we’ll be going through how to create an auction.
let { hash: allowance_hash } = await this._nft.approve(    AUCTIONMANAGER_ADDRESS,    this.state.newAuction.tokenId  );   console.log("Approve Transaction sent! Hash:", allowance_hash);  await this.provider.waitForTransaction(allowance_hash);  console.log("Transaction mined!");     let { hash } = await this._auctionManager.createAuction(    this.state.newAuction.endTime * 60,     ethers.utils.parseEther(this.state.newAuction.minIncrement.toString()),     ethers.utils.parseEther(this.state.newAuction.directBuyPrice.toString()),     ethers.utils.parseEther(this.state.newAuction.startPrice.toString()),        NFT_ADDRESS,     this.state.newAuction.tokenId   );  console.log("Transaction sent! Hash:", hash);  await this.provider.waitForTransaction(hash);    console.log("Transaction mined!");  alert(`Transaction sent! Hash: ${hash}`);

Here is the code for creating an auction, add it into your createAuction() function (around line 79).
 
Let’s break it down!

Let’s start with the first half, _nft.approve(). To recap: in Quest 10, we learnt that the approve function requires the address to send the NFT to and the token ID, hence the two arguments that we provided for the approve function. We will be using this approve function to transfer the NFT to the auction contract where it will be held until the auction is over. 

As you can see for the approve function, there is no output but as mentioned earlier, the contract object itself will produce an output separate from the smart contract. Of course, the smart contract output would be part of this output but in this case that portion will be null.  

After sending the approve transaction, it will wait until the transaction is published before moving on to create the auction, hence the .waitForTransaction().

Now let’s take a look at the second half, _auctionManager.createAuction(). As we learnt in Quest 10, the createAuction() function expects the end time, the minimum increment per bid, the direct buy price, the starting price, NFT contract address and the token ID. 

A few things to note here regarding input - the first being that the time is stored in seconds, therefore we multiply the value by 60. The second is that with regards to the starting price, direct buy price and the minimum increment, the ethers.utils.parseEther function formats the string value into a Big Number instance of the amount of wei. Wei is the smallest denomination of ether, which has 18 decimal places. All this input data is taken from the fields provided to the user, which we will see later on.

So now that you know what the createAuction() function does, let’s go through how we can get all the auctions from the auction manager smart contract!
Step 8: Getting the Auctions
For this step, we will be going through how to get the list of auctions from the auction manager smart contract and how the site will look after fetching the auctions’ list! 
let auctionsAddresses = await this._auctionManager.getAuctions();   let auctions = await this._auctionManager.getAuctionInfo(auctionsAddresses);      let new_auctions = [];  for (let i = 0; i < auctions.endTime.length; i++) {    let endTime = auctions.endTime[i].toNumber();    let tokenId = auctions.tokenIds[i].toNumber();    let auctionState = auctions.auctionState[i].toNumber();       let startPrice = ethers.utils.formatEther(auctions.startPrice[i]);    let directBuyPrice = ethers.utils.formatEther(auctions.directBuy[i]);    let highestBid = ethers.utils.formatEther(auctions.highestBid[i]);       let owner = auctions.owner[i];       let newAuction = {     endTime: endTime,     startPrice: startPrice,     owner: owner,     directBuyPrice: directBuyPrice,     tokenId: tokenId,     highestBid: highestBid,     auctionState: auctionState,     auctionAddress: auctionsAddresses[i],    };    new_auctions.push(newAuction);  }  this.setState({ auctions: new_auctions }); // Update the state

Here is the code for getting the auctions from the auction manager smart contract. Add the code to your getAuctions() function (around line 102).

Let’s break it down!

In the first line, we call the getAuctions() function of the auction manager smart contract. In Quest 10, we learnt that the getAuctions() function does not require any input and in return, will output a list of auction contract addresses. In short, we are using this function to get us the list of contract addresses so that we can use these in the next function we’ll be calling.

In the next line of code you can see that we call the getAuctionInfo() function of the same smart contract. Again, referencing back to Quest 10, we know that this function takes in a list of contract addresses and outputs a variety of arrays with a certain index that corresponds to a certain contract. For example, index 1 of all arrays refers to the same auction contract address.

So now that we have our list of auction data, we loop through the list, formatting each value so that it’ll be easier to handle and display later on. We append each item newAuction to an array new_auctions and save it in a state with the code setState().

Step 10: Setting an Active Auction
We define an ‘active’ contract as one that we want to focus on so that we can perform actions such as placing a bid, withdrawing a token, withdrawing funds, etc. The active auction can be triggered by clicking the ‘See More’ button on the web page (will be covered later).
let previousBids = await _this._auction.allBids(); // Get the bids let bids = []; // A list of bids for (let i = 0; i < previousBids[0].length; i++) {  // Loop through the bids  bids.push({   // Add the bid to the list   bidder: previousBids[0][i], // The bidder   bid: ethers.utils.formatEther(previousBids[1][i]), // The bid  }); } auction.bids = bids; let highestBidder = await _this._auction.maxBidder(); auction.highestBidder = highestBidder; let minIncrement = await _this._auction.minIncrement(); auction.minIncrement = ethers.utils.formatEther(minIncrement); _this.setState({ activeAuction: auction }); // Update the state

Add the code above to your setActiveFunction() function, after the code which you added in Step 5. This should be around line 142. 

Before we set the active auction, we will need to retrieve additional information that was not provided by the auction manager smart contract such as bid information, highest bidder as well as the minimum increment. 

We first start by getting all the bids using the _auction.allBids() function. As we have learnt in Quest 10, the allBids() function function returns a list of addresses and the bid amount associated with those addresses. After getting the array of addresses and their amounts, we will then need to format the data for easy display on the site. 

Once we have the bids, the next step is to get the highest bidder and we do so by calling the _auction.maxBidder() function. Going back to Quest 10, we have learnt that the maxBidder() function returns us the address of the highest bidder. We need to know the highest bidder so that we can programmatically prevent some functions such as withdrawing the token from occurring if the address is not the highest bidder. 

Now that we have the highest bidder, we will now need to get the minimum increment. As the function name dictates, the minIncrement() function returns the value of the minimum increment amount. The reason why we need it is so that the users can calculate the minimum amount that will be acceptable for their new bid. 

Once the active auction is set, the page will display all information retrieved here as well as the information retrieved from the getAuctionInfo() function in the previous steps. It will also display the appropriate buttons that will trigger functions such as placing a bid, withdrawing token, withdrawing funds and cancelling the auction. These four functions will be covered in the next few steps.
Step 11: Placing a Bid
In this step, we’ll be going through how to place a bid with an auction smart contract. Because this is an auction, we will need a function to handle users' bids. To place a bid, you will need to click on the ‘See More’ button of an active auction. This will also bring you to an auction page with more details on the auction (refer to image below).


Also note that since NFT owners cannot bid in an auction, you will need to switch accounts. Open up your Core wallet and change your account to the ‘Bidder’ account. Since the ‘Bidder’ needs to have some AVAX tokens before he/she can place a bid, you’ll need to fund this account before proceeding. You can either 1/ transfer AVAX from your first account to the ‘Bidder’ account or 2/ get tokens from the faucet. You’ll also need to refresh the page after you’ve switched accounts as the application needs to clear your old wallet data. 

Troubleshooting: if you have already submitted a request to the faucet in the past 24 hours and intend to make another request, you’ll notice that you’ll be faced with a 24 hour cooldown. Please try to identify the wallet that contains the previously located testnet tokens and transfer your tokens from that wallet instead. 

However, if you have lost access to that wallet and are still facing the cooldown blocker, you can request for Fuji AVAX testnet tokens from Avalanche’s Developer Relations team in their Discord server’s developers-chat. Note that this should not be your first option - be prudent with your testnet tokens.

So now that you are in your ‘Bidder’ account, you’ll notice that after pressing the ‘See More’ button, you now see another field that was not available to you when you were in the first account - you can now see the ‘Place Bid’ button.

Here is the code for placing a bid with the auction manager smart contract. 

let { hash } = await this._auction.placeBid({ value: amount });   await this.provider.waitForTransaction(hash);   alert(`Transaction sent! Hash: ${hash}`); // Show the transaction hash

This code will be triggered when the ‘Place Bid’ button is clicked on. Add this code to your placeBid() function (around line 322). 

Looking at the code, you will see that we used the placeBid() function of the auction smart contract with the amount that was typed in. As covered in Quest 10, the placeBid() function allows users to place a bid in an auction provided that the bid met certain requirements, in particular, the bid amount must be higher than the starting price and the highest bid. Once the placeBid() function is called, it will trigger your Core wallet to ask for confirmation on the transaction.

Now let’s try placing a bid! Make sure that your auction hasn’t ended yet (you can check how many more minutes your auction has by looking at ‘End Time’). Enter 0.6 as your bid amount and press on the ‘Place Bid’ button. If your auction has already ended, change back the Core account holding the NFTs and create another auction.

Similar to before, you’ll receive a popup from Core asking for your permission to sign the transaction. After you approve it, you’ll receive an alert stating the hash of your transaction and you’ll also see that your bid has been added to the list of bids. Awesome! Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference.

If there’s no change in your webpage, you might need to manually refresh it to view the changes.

Step 12: Withdrawing the NFT
For this step, we will be showing you how we can withdraw the NFT from the auction smart contract. This function is necessary so that the winners of the auction can withdraw their token when either 1/ the auction ends or 2/ they trigger a direct buy. 
let { hash } = await this._auction.withdrawToken(); await this.provider.waitForTransaction(hash); alert(`Withdrawal Successful! Hash: ${hash}`);

The code above is used for withdrawing the token from the auction manager smart contract. Add it to your withdrawToken() function around line 330. For this, we only need to call the withdrawToken() function on the auction smart contract. As covered in Quest 10, the withdrawToken() function of the auction smart contract checks if the auction has ended and if the address calling the wallet is the highest bidder. If it satisfies both conditions, it will send the token to that address. 

Let’s test this function out! Note that you’ll only be able to withdraw the token once one of the conditions mentioned above are achieved. In our case, it’ll be once the value of Auction State becomes ‘Ended’ (i.e. you’ll need to wait until the value of ‘End Time’ reaches 0). Once that happens, your page should look similar to the image below.


Press on ‘Withdraw Token’ and approve the transaction on your Core wallet popup. After the transaction goes through, your page should look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. Once you have successfully withdrawn the token, you will see the NFT with that ID that was put up for auction (e.g. ID 1 in the image in ‘Expected output’) is now part of your NFT list. Awesome!
Expected output
Step 13: Withdrawing the Funds
For this step, we will be going through how we withdraw the funds of a finished auction using the auction smart contract. The reason for this function is so that the token owners can withdraw the bid amount from the auction smart contract when the auction is over. 
let { hash } = await this._auction.withdrawFunds(); await this.provider.waitForTransaction(hash); alert(`Withdrawal Successful! Hash: ${hash}`);

The code to withdraw funds is shown above. Add the code above to your withdrawFunds() function (around line 339). In order to withdraw the funds, we only need to trigger the withdrawFunds() function in the auction smart contract. The withdrawFunds() function requires no input and the smart contract would only allow the token owner to perform this action. 

Since this function is only available to previous token owners, make sure your current Core account is switched to the account that owned the NFT before the auction ended. Also note that this function can only be called when the auction is completed and there was at least 1 bid placed. You’ll also need to refresh the page after you’ve switched accounts as the application needs to clear your old wallet data.

When the withdrawFunds() function is called, it will trigger the Core wallet to ask for confirmation for this transaction. After the transaction is sent, the application will wait until the transaction is published on the Avalanche Fuji Testnet before producing an alert. Your webpage will look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’.

If you look at the AVAX balance of the wallet that put the NFT up for the bid, you’ll see that its balance has now been updated with the bid amount. Almost at the end now, one last function to cover!

Step 14: Cancelling the Auction
How to start
For this step, we will be going through how we can cancel an auction through the auction smart contract. Of course, there are requirements in place for what auctions can be cancelled and we will be going through that in this step. The code to cancel an auction is as shown below; you’ll need to copy and paste the code to your cancelAuction() function (around line 348). 
let { hash } = await this._auction.cancelAuction();  await this.provider.waitForTransaction(hash);   alert(`Auction Canceled! Hash: ${hash}`);

In order to cancel the auction, we only need to call the cancelAuction() function on the auction smart contract. As we have learnt in Quest 10, the cancelAuction() function requires no input and only allows the token owner to call this function. Also, we learned that in order to cancel an auction, there must not be any existing bids and the auction must be active.  

Let’s test it out! If you don’t have an active auction, create a new one and press on ‘See More’. Your web page should look like the image in ‘How to start’ at this point. 

After pressing on ‘Cancel Auction’, there will be a Core wallet popup asking for your permission to approve the transaction. After approving the transaction, you’ll see that the NFT is now back in your wallet. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference if you are unsure (refer to the Cancelled auction state of token ID 3).

Step 15: Let’s Ace Your Submissions! Preparing Your Submission!
Great job following till the end! Last step - preparing the deliverables. 
Follow the instructions below to prepare your deliverables:
  1. Using your first account in Core, create an auction with the following details
    • Start Price - 0.3
    • Token Id - choose any ID in ‘Your items’
    • Minimum Increment - 0.15
    • Direct Buy Price - 1
    • Duration In Minutes - 10
  2. Change to the the ‘Bidder’ account, place a bid with a bid amount of 0.5
  3. Wait 10 minutes for the auction state to change to ‘Ended’
  4. Using the ‘Bidder’ account, withdraw the token
  5. Change to your first account and withdraw the funds

Now you’ll need to open three tabs of the SnowTrace block explorer:
  1. Your first account’s address
  2. Your second account’s address
  3. The deployed NFT contract address. Then, change to the ‘Events’ tab and expand the most recent event. It should be a transfer event

Now you’ll need to take a fullscreen screenshot of these three windows open. Note that for all three windows, the contract address must be clearly visible.

Your screenshot should show:
  • Your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
  • SnowTrace block explorer of your first account with the ‘Transactions’ tab open and the most recent two transactions clearly displayed
  • SnowTrace block explorer of the ‘Bidder’ account with the ‘Transactions’ tab open and the most recent transaction clearly displayed
  • SnowTrace block explorer of your NFT contract with the ‘Events’ tab open and the most recent event expanded so that the information is clearly displayed
  • For all three windows, the contract address must be clearly visible
  • Make sure that all parts visible in ‘Expected output’ are also visible in your screenshot(s)!

When labelling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided: C48a_Q11_yourstackupname.png.

If you are using multiple screenshots, name the first one C48a_Q11_1_yourstackupname.png, the second one C48a_Q11_2_yourstackupname.png and so on.

Refer to ‘Expected output’ if you are unsure.

Do note that as this is a re-run, you should not be using screenshots from the first run of the campaign.
